<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="194" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d194">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">768.72111/1960</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-03">
                                    <hi rend="italic">3 April, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I think that Mr.
                            Lansing has stated the case truly and conclusively. It is my own
                            judgment that we could not have adopted any other course consistently
                            with our obligations as neutrals.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>